{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What Props Spread Does"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "props spread"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " pattern ("
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "{...props}"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " in JSX) copies all properties of a JavaScript object as attributes on a component or element. It is the JSX equivalent of "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Object.assign"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " \u2014 every key/value pair in the spread object becomes a prop:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// Without spread \u2014 verbose\n<input\n  type={props.type}\n  value={props.value}\n  onChange={props.onChange}\n  className={props.className}\n  disabled={props.disabled}\n/>\n\n// With spread \u2014 equivalent\n<input {...props} />\n\n// Both compile to the same createElement call:\nReact.createElement('input', props)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Spread is most useful in "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "wrapper components"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " that accept all the same props as an underlying element without having to name each one explicitly."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Diagram comparing basic spread, destructure-plus-rest pattern, and prop override order in JSX spread",
          "title": null
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Basic Spread Pattern"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// Simplest wrapper: forward all props to the underlying element\nfunction TextInput(props) {\n  return <input {...props} />;\n}\n\n// Usage \u2014 any attribute valid on <input> passes through:\n<TextInput\n  type=\"email\"\n  value={email}\n  onChange={e => setEmail(e.target.value)}\n  placeholder=\"Enter email\"\n  required\n/>"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "This makes "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "TextInput"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " a transparent wrapper \u2014 it adds no behavior itself but could add styling, a ref, or context subscriptions without the caller needing to know."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Pure spreading ("
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "code"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "{...props}"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " with no extraction) works but may forward non-DOM props to a DOM element, causing React to warn in development: \"React does not recognize the X prop on a DOM element.\""
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Destructure and Rest: The Recommended Pattern"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The best practice is to extract the props your component uses and pass the remainder to the underlying element with the rest operator:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// Extract own props; forward everything else\nfunction Button({\n  variant = 'primary',   // Button's own prop\n  size = 'md',           // Button's own prop\n  className = '',        // Merging with own class\n  children,              // Button renders this\n  ...rest               // Everything else: type, onClick, disabled, aria-*, data-*, etc.\n}) {\n  const classes = [\n    'btn',\n    `btn-${variant}`,\n    `btn-${size}`,\n    className,\n  ].filter(Boolean).join(' ');\n\n  return (\n    <button className={classes} {...rest}>\n      {children}\n    </button>\n  );\n}\n\n// Usage:\n<Button\n  variant=\"danger\"\n  size=\"lg\"\n  onClick={handleDelete}\n  disabled={isDeleting}\n  data-testid=\"delete-btn\"\n  aria-describedby=\"delete-help\"\n>\n  Delete\n</Button>"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The component handles "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "variant"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "size"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "className"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " internally. Every other prop \u2014 "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "onClick"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "disabled"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", ARIA attributes, data attributes \u2014 flows through "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "rest"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " to the DOM "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "<button>"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " without being named explicitly."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Prop Override Order"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When the spread object and an explicit prop specify the same attribute, the last one wins \u2014 same as object literal property order:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// Your component fixes type=\"button\" (prevents form submission)\n// and allows callers to set other props, but NOT override type\nfunction SafeButton({ children, ...rest }) {\n  return (\n    <button\n      {...rest}        // spread first: caller's props\n      type=\"button\"   // explicit last: always wins, cannot be overridden\n    >\n      {children}\n    </button>\n  );\n}\n\n// Caller tries to override type \u2014 ignored:\n<SafeButton type=\"submit\" onClick={fn}>Go</SafeButton>\n// Renders: <button type=\"button\" onClick={fn}>Go</button>\n\n// REVERSED \u2014 caller can override type:\nfunction FlexibleButton({ children, ...rest }) {\n  return (\n    <button\n      type=\"button\"   // default first\n      {...rest}        // caller can override\n    >\n      {children}\n    </button>\n  );\n}\n\n<FlexibleButton type=\"submit\" onClick={fn}>Go</FlexibleButton>\n// Renders: <button type=\"submit\" onClick={fn}>Go</button>"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The convention: put your defaults "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "before"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " the spread (so callers can override them) and put your enforced values "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "after"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " the spread (so they cannot be overridden)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Spreading Onto Custom Components"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Spreading works on custom components, not just DOM elements. The spread passes props to the component function:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "const defaultFormProps = {\n  autoComplete: 'off',\n  noValidate: true,\n  onSubmit: e => e.preventDefault(),\n};\n\nfunction ProtectedForm({ children, ...rest }) {\n  return (\n    <form {...defaultFormProps} {...rest}>\n      {children}\n    </form>\n  );\n}\n\n// Composing component-level defaults:\nconst cardDefaults = {\n  variant: 'elevated',\n  padding: 'md',\n  rounded: true,\n};\n\nfunction FeaturedCard(props) {\n  return <Card {...cardDefaults} {...props} />;\n  // caller can override any default\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Merging className When Spreading"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "One challenge with spreading is "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "className"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " \u2014 if both the spread object and an explicit prop have "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "className"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", one overwrites the other. The solution is to merge them:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// Wrong: className from spread overwrites the local one (or vice versa)\nfunction Card({ className, ...rest }) {\n  return <div className={`card ${className}`} {...rest} />;\n  // If rest also contains className, it will overwrite everything\n}\n\n// Fix: extract className from rest, then merge\nfunction Card({ className = '', ...rest }) {\n  // className is extracted from rest \u2014 rest no longer has it\n  return <div className={`card ${className}`} {...rest} />;\n  // Now rest.className does not exist \u2014 safe to set className explicitly\n}\n\n// Usage:\n<Card className=\"featured\" data-id=\"123\">...</Card>\n// Renders: <div class=\"card featured\" data-id=\"123\">...</div>\n\n// With a classnames library for more complex merging:\nimport cx from 'classnames';\nfunction Card({ className, variant, ...rest }) {\n  return (\n    <div\n      className={cx('card', { [`card-${variant}`]: variant }, className)}\n      {...rest}\n    />\n  );\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Filtering Props Before Spreading"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Sometimes you need to spread a large prop object but exclude specific keys \u2014 for example, remove internal routing props before passing to a DOM element:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// Remove router-specific props before passing to a native <a>\nfunction Link({ to, replace, state, ...rest }) {\n  // to, replace, state are consumed by the router \u2014 not valid DOM props\n  const href = resolveHref(to);\n  return <a href={href} {...rest} />;\n}\n\n// Filter by a list of known internal props:\nconst OWN_PROPS = new Set(['variant', 'size', 'isLoading', 'leftIcon', 'rightIcon']);\n\nfunction Button(props) {\n  const domProps = Object.fromEntries(\n    Object.entries(props).filter(([key]) => !OWN_PROPS.has(key))\n  );\n  const { variant = 'primary', size = 'md', isLoading, leftIcon, rightIcon } = props;\n  return (\n    <button className={`btn btn-${variant} btn-${size}`} {...domProps}>\n      {leftIcon}\n      {isLoading ? <Spinner /> : props.children}\n      {rightIcon}\n    </button>\n  );\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Spreading in Higher-Order Components"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Higher-order components (HOCs) almost always use props spreading to pass through props to the wrapped component:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "function withAuth(WrappedComponent) {\n  return function AuthenticatedComponent(props) {\n    const { currentUser } = useAuth();\n\n    if (!currentUser) {\n      return <Redirect to=\"/login\" />;\n    }\n\n    // Pass all original props plus the injected user prop\n    return <WrappedComponent user={currentUser} {...props} />;\n    // user comes first, so callers can override it with their own user prop\n  };\n}\n\nconst AuthenticatedDashboard = withAuth(Dashboard);\n// Usage:\n<AuthenticatedDashboard theme=\"dark\" layout=\"grid\" />"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The HOC adds a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "user"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " prop and forwards everything else. Because "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "user"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " comes before "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "{...props}"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", a caller who passes their own "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "user"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " prop will override the injected one."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "TypeScript and Props Spreading"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "TypeScript requires you to type the rest props correctly. The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "React.ComponentPropsWithoutRef"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and similar utility types help:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import React from 'react';\n\n// Type for a button that accepts all native button props\ntype ButtonProps = {\n  variant?: 'primary' | 'secondary' | 'danger';\n  isLoading?: boolean;\n} & React.ComponentPropsWithoutRef<'button'>;\n\nfunction Button({ variant = 'primary', isLoading, className, children, ...rest }: ButtonProps) {\n  return (\n    <button\n      className={[`btn-${variant}`, className].filter(Boolean).join(' ')}\n      disabled={isLoading}\n      {...rest}\n    >\n      {isLoading ? <Spinner /> : children}\n    </button>\n  );\n}\n\n// TypeScript will catch spreading unknown props at call sites\n<Button unknownProp={true} /> // TS error: unknownProp is not in ButtonProps"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When Not to Spread"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Props spreading is convenient but has trade-offs:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Explicit is better for public APIs. "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "If a component is widely used, listing its accepted props explicitly makes the API self-documenting and prevents accidental forwarding of internal state."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Avoid spreading at every level. "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "If every component in a chain spreads, debugging becomes hard \u2014 a prop accidentally passed at the top will propagate all the way down and cause confusing DOM warnings."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Spreading user-supplied objects can be dangerous. "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Never spread untrusted data (from APIs or user input) directly as props. Always destructure and validate the fields you actually expect."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// BAD: spreading untrusted data\nfunction Profile({ userData }) {\n  // userData came from an API \u2014 could have any shape\n  return <div {...userData} />; // dangerous! Could set onClick, style, etc.\n}\n\n// GOOD: extract only what you need\nfunction Profile({ userData }) {\n  const { name, bio, avatarUrl } = userData;\n  return (\n    <div>\n      <img src={avatarUrl} alt={name} />\n      <h1>{name}</h1>\n      <p>{bio}</p>\n    </div>\n  );\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Summary"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Props spreading ("
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "{...props}"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ") copies all properties from an object as JSX attributes. The destructure-and-rest pattern \u2014 extracting your component's own props and spreading the rest to the underlying element \u2014 is the recommended approach: it prevents unknown-prop warnings, keeps the component's own interface explicit, and allows safe forwarding. Prop override order follows JavaScript object semantics: later props overwrite earlier ones. Put defaults before the spread for caller-overridable defaults; put enforced values after for immutable ones. Always extract "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "className"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " before spreading to avoid having it overwritten by a later spread. Never spread untrusted external data."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Spreading Ref and forwardRef"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When a component wraps a DOM element and you want callers to pass a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "ref",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", use "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "React.forwardRef",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " alongside spreading. Without "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "forwardRef",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "ref",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " in the spread is silently ignored."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "tsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// Correct: forwardRef + spread\nconst Input = React.forwardRef<HTMLInputElement, React.ComponentPropsWithoutRef<'input'>>(\n  ({ className, ...rest }, ref) => (\n    <input\n      ref={ref}\n      className={`input-base ${className ?? ''}`}\n      {...rest}\n    />\n  )\n);\n\n// Usage: ref works as expected\nconst ref = useRef<HTMLInputElement>(null);\n<Input ref={ref} placeholder=\"Search\" />"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "React.ComponentPropsWithoutRef<'input'>",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " type provides every valid HTML input attribute. Destructuring "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "className",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " before spreading lets you merge it with a base class, while "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "ref",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is forwarded through the second argument."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Prop Spreading and Performance"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Each render creates a new spread object. For most components this cost is negligible, but components wrapped in "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "React.memo",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " need careful attention: if the object reference changes every render, memo's shallow comparison fails."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "tsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// Problem: new object every render breaks memo\nconst ChildMemo = React.memo(Child);\n\nfunction Parent({ id, onClick, ...rest }) {\n  // 'rest' is a new object each render \u2192 memo never bails out\n  return <ChildMemo id={id} {...rest} onClick={onClick} />;\n}\n\n// Fix: pass only what the child needs\nfunction Parent({ id, onClick, theme }) {\n  return <ChildMemo id={id} onClick={onClick} theme={theme} />;\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "If spreading is necessary inside a memoized subtree, consider "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "useMemo",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " to stabilise the extra props object when its source values have not changed."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Common Pitfalls and Debugging"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Unknown DOM attributes: ",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Spreading custom component props onto a DOM element sends unknown attributes to the DOM and triggers React warnings. Always destructure component-only props and pass only the remaining HTML-safe attributes."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Silent overrides: ",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Props listed after the spread override whatever came from the spread, and props before it can be overridden by the spread. Wrong order silently swallows explicit props \u2014 review order every time you add a spread."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Event handler conflicts: ",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "If both the spread and an explicit prop supply "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "onClick",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ", only one survives. Compose them instead: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "onClick={() => { rest.onClick?.(); handleClick(); }}",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Spreading at multiple levels: ",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "If a wrapper spreads to an inner wrapper which also spreads, any extra key propagates all the way to the DOM. Audit the chain when you see unknown attribute warnings."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "JSON serialisation: ",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Spreading is a runtime operation. Server-side rendering and prop serialisation cannot spread \u2014 if you are passing serialised props over a network boundary, use explicit keys."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Key takeaways: "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "{...props} spreads all properties as JSX attributes. Destructure own props, spread rest to the underlying element. Last prop wins (Object.assign semantics). Default before spread = caller can override. Enforced after spread = cannot be overridden. Extract className before spread to merge it safely. Never spread unvalidated external data."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}